description.value: A small Bes-jar of coarse red siltware pottery, with a blunt pointed base and convex sides. The narrow mouth is surrounded by a short, cylindrical neck, which was finished with a slightly flared rim. The rim has been broken and all the original top edge is missing. The coarse fabric shows voids from burned-out straw. On the exterior is a red slip, worn off in places. The side of the vase is decorated with a very abbreviated Bes-face, formed of applied blobs of clay for the ears and eyes, the latter set in a slight depression.

Squat vase of the higher type, made of magnesite: the mouth is very narrow and it has a raised external rim.
